'68:27': [
{sup:"1a", word:"Benjamin", vrefs:"1&nbsp;Sam. 9:21", lines:["In the praise rendered to God by His elect in vv. {Psa68:24|24}-{Psa68:28|28}, a scenery in typology is portrayed concerning God&rsquo;s New Testament economy in the accomplishing of God&rsquo;s redemption by Christ for God&rsquo;s salvation and in the spreading of the glad tidings of Christ&rsquo;s accomplishment with the goodly words of the gospel. Benjamin, mentioned here, had two names, the first of which was Ben-oni. This name, given to him by his mother Rachel as she was dying in childbirth, means son of my affliction ({Gen35:18|Gen. 35:18a}). As the son of affliction, Benjamin typifies Christ, who, as the man of sorrows ({Isa53:3|Isa. 53:3}) in His incarnation and human life on earth, accomplished God&rsquo;s eternal redemption for His full salvation ({Heb9:12|Heb. 9:12}). Whereas Rachel named her son Ben-oni, Jacob immediately changed the child&rsquo;s name to Benjamin, which means son of the right hand ({Gen35:18|Gen. 35:18b}). To be at the right hand is to be in a position of glory and honor. As the son of the right hand, Benjamin typifies Christ, who, as the Son of the right hand in His resurrection, victory, and ascension, ministers in the heavens to carry out the application of God&rsquo;s redemption for His salvation ({Heb8:1|Heb. 8:1}-{Heb8:2|2}; {Heb7:25|7:25}). Christ was incarnated to be Ben-oni, the man of sorrows, but in resurrection He became Benjamin, the Son of the right hand in glory and honor ({Psa80:17|80:17}; {Mrk16:19|Mark 16:19}; {Act2:33|Acts 2:33}; {Act5:31|5:31})."]},
{sup:"2b", word:"Judah", vrefs:"Gen. 49:8-10", lines:["Judah is the lion with the power and the scepter, and he is the peace (Shiloh) to God&rsquo;s people ({Rev5:5|Rev. 5:5a}; {Gen49:8|Gen. 49:8}-{Gen49:10|10}). Whereas Benjamin typifies Christ mainly in His humanity, Judah typifies Christ mainly in His divinity. In His divinity Christ is not a man of sorrows but a lion with power and authority (signified by the scepter). In particular, Judah typifies Christ as the victory for God&rsquo;s people and the peace to God&rsquo;s people. In the application of redemption, Christ is our peace ({Eph2:14|Eph. 2:14}-{Eph2:15|15}).","Judah, the kingly tribe, was accompanied always by Benjamin, a warrior tribe ({Gen49:27|Gen. 49:27}), for God&rsquo;s kingdom on the earth. In typology Judah and Benjamin, who were joined geographically, form a group for the accomplishment and application of Christ&rsquo;s redemption for God&rsquo;s salvation. With Benjamin the emphasis is on the accomplishment of redemption; with Judah the emphasis is on the application (in Christ&rsquo;s ascension) of redemption."]},
{sup:"3c", word:"Zebulun", vrefs:"Gen. 49:13; Matt. 4:15", lines:["Dwelling at the shore of the sea (Galilee) and being a shore for ships ({Gen49:13|Gen. 49:13}), Zebulun typifies Christ as the &ldquo;shore&rdquo; of the evangelists for the transportation and spreading in the preaching of God&rsquo;s gospel. After Christ accomplished all the things that are to be proclaimed as the gospel, on the day of Pentecost at least 120 gospel &ldquo;ships,&rdquo; all of whom were Galileans ({Act2:7|Acts 2:7}; {Act13:31|13:31}), set out from the &ldquo;shore&rdquo; to spread the gospel. See {Gen49:13^1|note 13<sup>1</sup>} in {Gen49|Gen. 49}."]},
{sup:"4d", word:"Naphtali", vrefs:"Gen. 49:21", lines:["According to {Gen49:21|Gen. 49:21} (see {Gen49:21^1|note} there), Naphtali is a hind let loose, and he gives beautiful words. Naphtali typifies Christ as the One who is released from death in resurrection, signified by the hind let loose ({Psa22:Title|Psa. 22, title}; {SoS2:8|S.S. 2:8}-{SoS2:9|9}), and gives beautiful words for the preaching of His gospel ({Mat28:18|Matt. 28:18}-{Mat28:20|20}).","In typology Zebulun and Naphtali form a group for the spreading and the propagating of the glad tidings of Christ&rsquo;s redemption, accomplished for God&rsquo;s salvation. The people of both Zebulun and Naphtali were men of Galilee ({Mat4:12|Matt. 4:12}-{Mat4:17|17}; {Act1:11|Acts 1:11}), from whom the gospel of Christ has been spread, preached, and propagated."]},
],
'68:28': [
{sup:1, word:"Strengthen", lines:["The word in vv. {Psa68:28|28b}-{Psa68:29|29a} indicates that after God&rsquo;s strengthening of what He has done for His elect, the influence of the enjoyment of God in His house spreads to the entire city of Jerusalem because of the house of God, which was at Jerusalem. The house of God signifies the local churches, and the city of Jerusalem signifies the kingdom, the strengthening and the safeguard of the church."]},
],
'68:29': [
{sup:1, word:"Kings", lines:["The word in vv. {Psa68:29|29b}-{Psa68:35|35} indicates that the influence of the enjoyment of God in His house and His city will gain the whole earth for God. The scenery portrayed in these verses will consummate in the coming age of restoration ({Mat19:28|Matt. 19:28}; {Act3:20|Acts 3:20}-{Act3:21|21}), in which all the earth will come to Jerusalem to worship God and to receive instruction and enlightenment ({Isa2:2|Isa. 2:2}-{Isa2:3|3}; {Zec8:20|Zech. 8:20}-{Zec8:23|23}; {Zec14:16|14:16})."]},
{sup:"a", word:"gift", vrefs:"2&nbsp;Sam. 8:2, 6; 1&nbsp;Kings 4:21; Psa. 72:10; 76:11; Rev. 21:24"},
],
