'73:1': [
{sup:1, word:"Surely", lines:["The first four psalms in Book Three, {Psa73|Psa. 73}&mdash;{Psa76|76}, cover four matters: the personal sufferings of the seeking saints ({Psa73|Psa. 73}), the desolation of God&rsquo;s house ({Psa74|Psa. 74}), the judgment of Christ on the desolators ({Psa75|Psa. 75}), and the victory of God in His dwelling place ({Psa76|Psa. 76})."]},
{sup:"2a", word:"pure", vrefs:"Psa. 24:4; 51:10; Matt. 5:8; 1&nbsp;Tim. 1:5", lines:["To be pure in heart is to have God as our one goal and aim. See {Mat5:8^1|note 8<sup>1</sup>} in {Mat5|Matt. 5}."]},
],
'73:2': [
{sup:1, word:"turned", lines:["Verses {Psa73:2|2}-{Psa73:16|16} are a record of the suffering of the seeking psalmist and his perplexity because of the prosperity of the wicked. Whereas {Psa1:3|Psa. 1:3}-{Psa1:4|4} says that the law-keeper prospers and the wicked do not prosper, here the psalmist was puzzled ({Psa73:16|v. 16}) and nearly stumbled by his own suffering (vv. {Psa73:13|13}-{Psa73:14|14}) and the prosperity of the wicked, who are at ease and heap up riches ({Psa73:12|v. 12}). See {Psa1:3^1|note 3<sup>1</sup>} in {Psa1|Psa. 1}."]},
],
'73:3': [
{sup:"a", word:"prosperity", vrefs:"Jer. 12:1"},
],
'73:9': [
{sup:"a", word:"tongue", vrefs:"Psa. 12:3-4; 120:2-4; James 3:5"},
],
'73:12': [
{sup:"a", word:"heap", vrefs:"cf. Psa. 39:6; Luke 12:20"},
],
'73:13': [
{sup:1, word:"vain", lines:["The psalmist considered that he had purified his heart in vain because, instead of enjoying material prosperity, he was plagued all day long and chastened every morning ({Psa73:14|v. 14}). However, the real vanity is anything besides God. Idols are vanity; material prosperity is vanity; anything other than God is vanity ({Ecc1:2|Eccl. 1:2}). A pure heart is one that is set on nothing but God. The psalmist realized this when he entered into the sanctuary of God (vv. {Psa73:17|17}, {Psa73:25|25}-{Psa73:26|26}; see notes {Psa73:25^1|25<sup>1</sup>} and {Psa73:26^1|26<sup>1</sup>})."]},
{sup:"a", word:"washed", vrefs:"Psa. 24:4; 26:6; cf. Deut. 21:6"},
],
'73:17': [
{sup:"1a", word:"sanctuary", vrefs:"Psa. 20:2; 77:13", lines:["The solution to the psalmist&rsquo;s perplexity concerning the prosperity of the wicked was obtained in God&rsquo;s sanctuary. First, God&rsquo;s sanctuary, His habitation, is in our spirit ({Eph2:22|Eph. 2:22}) and, second, it is the church ({1Ti3:15|1&nbsp;Tim. 3:15}). Thus, to go into the sanctuary of God, we need to turn to our spirit and go to the meetings of the church. Once we are in the sanctuary&mdash;in the spirit and in the church&mdash;we will have another view, a particular perception, of the situation concerning the wicked (vv. {Psa73:18|18}-{Psa73:20|20}). In our spirit and in the church we receive divine revelation and obtain the explanation to all our problems."]},
],
